data.content:
## Error 1 — `left && right` (DynamicOps.cs)

The `&&` operator desugars into `operator true(left) ? left : operator &(left, right)`. When `right` is `dynamic`, the entire expression is dynamically bound. However, C# 15 now **recognizes `operator true`/`false` declared on interfaces** during this resolution. The dynamic runtime binder **cannot invoke static operators defined on an interface** — it only sees operators on concrete types at runtime. In earlier versions, the interface-level `operator true`/`false` was simply ignored in this context.

**Fix:** Avoid mixing interface-typed operands (that define `operator true`/`false`) with `dynamic` in short-circuit expressions:

```csharp
void Apply(IFilter left, dynamic right)
{
    // Option A: cast to the concrete type
    var combined = (CompositeFilter)left && right;

    // Option B: desugar manually
    IFilter evaluated = left ? left & (IFilter)right : left;
}
```

---

## Error 2 — `ref readonly` lambda (RefHelper.cs)

CS0518 ("Predefined type is not defined or imported") means the compiler expects a **BCL type that isn't in your target framework**. C# 15 changed how `ref readonly` return lambdas are lowered — they now require `System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RequiresLocationAttribute` (or a similar new metadata type) that only ships with the **.NET 11 runtime libraries**.

This typically happens when you upgraded the **compiler/SDK** but your project still targets an older TFM (e.g., `net10.0`).

**Fix:** Ensure your project actually targets .NET 11:

```xml
<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>
```

Or, if you must target an older framework, define the missing type yourself:

```csharp
namespace System.Runtime.CompilerServices
{
    [AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Parameter)]
    internal sealed class RequiresLocationAttribute : Attribute { }
}
```
